127, 128. There are serious difficulties in this description, obviously sarcastic, of the armed equestrian statue of a lawyer. A spent-shaft should be straight; why is it curvatum here? M. explains that the shalt bends when poised for the throw; but it would be strange to represent this in a statue. Friedl. suggests that curv. isused for rotatum, ‘brandished,' but gives no similar instance.

lusca offers a second difficulty: various explanations are given, ag. that the statue has one eye closed, as taking aim; that the statue is seen in profile; that Aemilius may have been luscus himself. From the point of view of art, all 'these are unsatisfactory. Friedl. suggests that the eye-hails were, as often, represented by coloured stones, one of which has fallen out.

If we accept the last view, perhaps curvatum may be ‘crooked, out of the perpendicular’: Juv. then means that the statue is badly wrought and in bad repair.
